  "prompt": "What happens if you overdose on Naproxen?",
  "response": "Overdosing on naproxen, a nonsteroidal anti-inflammatory drug (NSAID) commonly used to relieve pain, inflammation, and fever, can be serious and potentially life-threatening. If someone has taken more naproxen than recommended, it's crucial to seek immediate medical attention. \n\n**Symptoms of a naproxen overdose may include:**\n\n- **Gastrointestinal Issues:** Nausea, vomiting, stomach pain, and gastrointestinal bleeding.\n- **Central Nervous System Effects:** Dizziness, headache, drowsiness, confusion, or seizures.\n- **Respiratory Problems:** Difficulty breathing or slowed breathing.\n- **Cardiovascular Symptoms:** Rapid or irregular heartbeat, low blood pressure.\n- **Kidney Effects:** Reduced urine output or kidney failure.\n- **Metabolic Issues:** High blood sugar levels or metabolic acidosis.\n- **Others:** Ringing in the ears (tinnitus), blurred vision, or rash.\n\n**What to Do in Case of an Overdose:**\n\n1. **Immediate Action:** If an overdose is suspected, contact emergency medical services right away or go to the nearest emergency room.\n2. **Provide Information:** Be prepared to provide information about the amount of naproxen taken, the time of ingestion, and any other substances that may have been consumed.\n3. **Do Not Induce Vomiting:** Unless instructed by a healthcare professional, do not try to make the person vomit, as this could cause additional harm.\n\n**Prevention Tips:**\n\n- **Follow Dosage Instructions:** Always take naproxen exactly as prescribed by a healthcare provider or as indicated on the packaging.\n- **Keep Medications Secure:** Store medications out of reach of children and individuals who might misuse them.\n- **Be Aware of Interactions:** Inform your healthcare provider about all the medications and supplements you are taking to avoid harmful interactions.\n\n**Note:** This information is not a substitute for professional medical advice. If you or someone else is experiencing a medical emergency, please seek immediate help from a qualified healthcare provider.",
